gw.testharness

Annotation Type IncludeModulesBeforeEnterRunLevel

  • Deprecated.

    @Retention(value=RUNTIME)
 @Target(value=TYPE)
 @Inherited
 @TagHandler(value=com.guidewire.testharness.taghandlers.IncludeModulesBeforeEnterRunLevelTagHandler.class)
 @Deprecated
public @interface IncludeModulesBeforeEnterRunLevel
    Declares a list of test modules to be included in the configuration for the duration of this test.

    • Required Element Summary

      Required Elements 
      Modifier and Type Required Element and Description
      java.lang.String[] value
      Deprecated. 
      The roots of the modules to use.

    • Element Detail

      • value

        public abstract java.lang.String[] value
        Deprecated. 
        The roots of the modules to use. Each module will be included in the order specified. A root can either be specified relative to the test source, or relative to the dev root.

        When determining the actual directory to use for a root, the test source is examined first. If the specified root is found under the test source directory, then that directory is used; otherwise, the dev source root is examined. If the specified root is found under the dev source root directory, then that directory is used. Otherwise, the source directory cannot be determined and an exception is thrown.

        When naming a test module, please use the following convention:

        • Name the module directory "testConfigXXXX", where XXXX describes what the module does (e.g. testConfigNoACL, testConfigRuleLogging).
        • Add a file to the module directory named "testConfigXXXX.txt", which is a readme file explaining what the module does. Using the same name for this file will allow users to easily find modules in IntelliJ, for example typing "CTRL-SHIFT-N testCo" will give a list of files describing the available modules.
